```java
// Default: REQUIRED — join existing TX or create new one
@Transactional
public void transfer(Long from, Long to, BigDecimal amount) {
    Account sender = accountRepo.findByIdForUpdate(from); // pessimistic
    Account receiver = accountRepo.findById(to).orElseThrow();
    sender.debit(amount);
    receiver.credit(amount);
    // TX commits on method exit — both accounts updated atomically
}

// REQUIRES_NEW — always new TX (useful for audit logging)
@Transactional(propagation = Propagation.REQUIRES_NEW)
public void auditLog(String action) {
    // Committed even if caller transaction rolls back
}
```

**Common mistake:** Calling `@Transactional` methods from within the same class. Spring proxies only intercept calls from outside the bean — self-invocation bypasses the proxy.

The most common performance issue in web applications using ORM:

<pre><code>// ❌ N+1 problem: 1 query for deliveries + 1 query PER delivery for stops
List&lt;Delivery&gt; deliveries = repo.findAll(); // 1 query: SELECT * FROM delivery
for (Delivery d : deliveries) {
    d.getStops().size(); // N queries: SELECT * FROM stop WHERE delivery_id = ?
}
// 100 deliveries = 101 queries!</code></pre>

<strong>Solutions:</strong>
<pre><code>// 1. JOIN FETCH (JPQL) — single query with JOIN
@Query("SELECT d FROM Delivery d JOIN FETCH d.stops WHERE d.status = :status")
List&lt;Delivery&gt; findWithStops(@Param("status") DeliveryStatus status);

// 2. @EntityGraph — declarative eager fetching
@EntityGraph(attributePaths = {"stops", "driver"})
List&lt;Delivery&gt; findByStatus(DeliveryStatus status);

// 3. Batch fetching (Hibernate) — reduces N+1 to N/batch+1
@BatchSize(size = 25)  // loads stops in batches of 25
private List&lt;Stop&gt; stops;</code></pre>

<strong>Detection:</strong> Enable SQL logging in dev, count queries per request. If you see the same query repeated with different IDs → N+1.

```java
@Entity
@Table(name = "post")  // explicit table name
public class Post {

    @Id
    @GeneratedValue(strategy = GenerationType.SEQUENCE)
    private Long id;

    @Column(nullable = false, length = 255)
    private String title;

    @Version  // optimistic locking
    private int version;

    @Enumerated(EnumType.STRING)  // never ORDINAL in production
    private PostStatus status;

    @Column(updatable = false)  // set once, never changed
    private LocalDateTime createdOn;

    @Lob  // large text
    private String content;
}
```

**Rules:**
- Always use `@Version` for optimistic locking in web apps
- `EnumType.STRING` — never `ORDINAL` (breaks when enum order changes)
- Prefer `LocalDateTime` over `Date` (immutable, no timezone confusion)
- `FetchType.LAZY` is the default for collections — keep it that way

**1. MultipleBagFetchException:**
Cannot JOIN FETCH two `List<>` collections simultaneously (produces Cartesian product).
```java
// ❌ Throws MultipleBagFetchException
SELECT p FROM Post p JOIN FETCH p.comments JOIN FETCH p.tags

// ✅ Use Set<> instead of List<>, or fetch in separate queries
```

**2. Pagination + JOIN FETCH:**
```java
// ❌ Hibernate fetches ALL rows, then paginates in-memory!
Query q = em.createQuery("SELECT p FROM Post p JOIN FETCH p.comments");
q.setFirstResult(0);
q.setMaxResults(10);
// WARNING: HHH000104: firstResult/maxResults with collection fetch
```
Solution: Paginate the parent query, then batch-fetch children with `@BatchSize(size=25)`.

**3. N+1 in disguise:**
Accessing a lazy field in a loop (e.g., in a JSF template, a Jackson serializer, or a `toString()` method) triggers N queries silently.

Instead of JOIN FETCH (which complicates pagination), use `@BatchSize` on the collection:

```java
@OneToMany(mappedBy = "post", fetch = FetchType.LAZY)
@BatchSize(size = 25)  // load comments for 25 posts at once
private List<Comment> comments;
```

With `@BatchSize(25)`, accessing `post.getComments()` for the first time loads comments for up to 25 already-loaded posts in a single `WHERE post_id IN (?, ?, ..., ?)` query.

**Trade-off:** Not as optimal as JOIN FETCH for single-entity fetches, but works cleanly with pagination and doesn't require query changes.

**When to use entities:** You plan to modify the data (UPDATE/DELETE).
**When to use DTOs:** Read-only views (lists, reports, APIs).

```java
// ✅ Interface projection (Spring Data)
public interface PostSummary {
    Long getId();
    String getTitle();
    int getCommentCount();
}

// ✅ Class projection (JPQL constructor)
@Query("SELECT new com.app.dto.PostSummaryDTO(p.id, p.title, SIZE(p.comments)) FROM Post p")
List<PostSummaryDTO> findSummaries();
```

**Performance advantage:** No dirty checking, no Persistence Context overhead, only selected columns fetched from DB. For a list of 1000 records, this is significantly faster than loading 1000 full entities.

Use Criteria API when the query structure depends on runtime conditions (filters, search):

```java
CriteriaBuilder cb = em.getCriteriaBuilder();
CriteriaQuery<Post> cq = cb.createQuery(Post.class);
Root<Post> root = cq.from(Post.class);

List<Predicate> predicates = new ArrayList<>();

if (status != null) {
    predicates.add(cb.equal(root.get("status"), status));
}
if (author != null) {
    predicates.add(cb.equal(root.get("author"), author));
}
if (fromDate != null) {
    predicates.add(cb.greaterThanOrEqualTo(root.get("createdOn"), fromDate));
}

cq.where(predicates.toArray(new Predicate[0]));
cq.orderBy(cb.desc(root.get("createdOn")));

return em.createQuery(cq).setMaxResults(20).getResultList();
```

**When NOT to use:** Static queries known at compile time → JPQL is more readable.

The most common JPA performance issue. When loading a collection lazily, Hibernate executes 1 query for the parent + N queries for each child.

```java
// ❌ N+1: 1 query for posts + N queries for comments
List<Post> posts = em.createQuery("SELECT p FROM Post p", Post.class).getResultList();
for (Post p : posts) {
    p.getComments().size(); // triggers lazy load → 1 SELECT per post
}

// ✅ JOIN FETCH: 1 single query
List<Post> posts = em.createQuery(
    "SELECT p FROM Post p JOIN FETCH p.comments", Post.class
).getResultList();
```

**Detection:** Enable `hibernate.generate_statistics=true` and look for high query counts relative to entity counts.

The EntityManager (1st-level cache) defers all SQL until flush time. This means:

1. **Reduced lock time** — locks acquired only at flush, not at each `persist()`
2. **Batch opportunity** — all statements available at once for batching
3. **Dirty checking** — only changed fields generate UPDATE

**Pitfall:** The Persistence Context grows with every managed entity. In batch processing, flush + clear periodically:

```java
for (int i = 0; i < 10_000; i++) {
    em.persist(entity);
    if (i % 50 == 0) {
        em.flush();
        em.clear(); // detach all — free memory
    }
}
```

The 2nd-level cache (L2) is shared across sessions/transactions. Candidates: entities read frequently, written rarely.

| Strategy | Use case |
|----------|----------|
| `READ_ONLY` | Immutable reference data (countries, enums) |
| `READ_WRITE` | Read-heavy, occasional writes (products, categories) |
| `NONSTRICT_READ_WRITE` | Tolerates brief staleness |

```java
@Entity
@Cacheable
@Cache(usage = CacheConcurrencyStrategy.READ_WRITE)
public class Category { ... }
```

**Never cache:** high-write entities (orders, events, logs), large collections, or entities accessed by multiple apps writing directly to the DB.

**Optimistic locking** (preferred for web apps):
```java
@Version
private int version; // auto-incremented on UPDATE
// Throws OptimisticLockException if version changed between read and write
```

**Pessimistic locking** (for critical sections):
```java
em.find(Account.class, id, LockModeType.PESSIMISTIC_WRITE);
// SELECT ... FOR UPDATE — blocks other transactions
```

**Rule of thumb:** Use optimistic by default. Switch to pessimistic only when conflict probability is high AND retry cost is unacceptable.

For read-only views (reports, lists, APIs), fetch only what you need:

```java
// ❌ Loads full entity graph into Persistence Context
List<Order> orders = em.createQuery("FROM Order", Order.class).getResultList();

// ✅ DTO projection — no managed entities, no dirty checking overhead
List<OrderSummaryDTO> summaries = em.createQuery(
    "SELECT new OrderSummaryDTO(o.id, o.total, o.status) FROM Order o",
    OrderSummaryDTO.class
).getResultList();
```

**Guideline:** Fetch entities only when you plan to modify them. For everything else, use projections.
